      <exercise workspace="1.3in" category="essential">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Express each statement below as a compound proposition in symbolic form. Clearly state the interpretation of the statements <m>p</m> and <m>q</m> stand for.
          </p>

          <p>
            <ol cols="1" marker="(a)">
              <li>
                The number <m>8</m> is both even and a power of <m>2</m>.
              </li>
              <li>
                The matrix <m>A</m> is not invertible.
              </li>
              <li>
                The number <m>x</m> equals zero, but the number <m>y</m> does not.
              </li>
              <li>
                There is an assignment scheduled for Wednesday or Friday.
              </li>
              <li>
                <q>Human beings want to be good, but not too good, and not all the time</q> (George Orwell).
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>

        <solution>
          <p>
            <ol marker="(a)">
              <li>
                We define the propositions <m>p</m> and <m>q</m> as <q>The number 8 is even</q> and <q>The number 8 is a power of 2</q> respectively. Then the given statement can be written symbolically as <m>p \wedge q</m>.
              </li>

              <li>
                Let <m>p</m> be the proposition <q>The matrix <m>A</m> is invertible</q>. Then the given statement can be written symbolically as <m>\neg p</m>.
              </li>

              <li>
                <p>
                  Define the propositions <m>p</m> and <m>q</m> as
                  <ul>
                    <li>
                      <p>
                        <m>p</m>: The number <m>x</m> equals zero.
                      </p>
                    </li>

                    <li>
                      <p>
                        <m>q</m>: The number <m>y</m> equals zero.
                      </p>
                    </li>
                  </ul>

                  The statement is equivalent to <m>p \vee q</m>.
                </p>
              </li>

              <li>
                Let <m>p</m> be the proposition <q>There is an assignment scheduled for Wednesday</q>, and let <m>q</m> be the proposition <q>There is an assignment scheduled for Friday</q>. Then the statement is equivalent to <m>p \vee q</m>.
              </li>

              <li>
                <p>
                  Define the propositions <m>p</m>, <m>q</m>, and <m>r</m> as follows:
                  <ul>
                    <li>
                      <m>p</m>: Human beings want to be good.
                    </li>

                    <li>
                      <m>q</m>: Human beings want to be too good.
                    </li>

                    <li>
                      <m>r</m>: Human beings want to be good all the time.
                    </li>
                  </ul>

                  We can then express the given quotation in symbolic form as <m>p \wedge \neg q \wedge \neg r</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </solution>

