  <page>
    <exercise workspace="1.1in" category="essential">
      <statement>
        <p>
          If <m>p \wedge q \rightarrow r \vee s</m> is false, find the truth values of <m>p</m>, <m>q</m>, <m>r</m>, and <m>s</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>

      <hint>
        <p>
          This can be done without a truth table.
        </p>
      </hint>

      <solution>
        <p>
          An implication statement can only be false if the antecedent is true, and the consequent is false. Thus if <m>p \wedge q \rightarrow r \vee s</m> is false, then <m>p \wedge q</m> must be true, and <m>r \vee s</m> must be false. Since <m>p \wedge q</m> is true, both <m>p</m> and <m>q</m> must be true. If <m>r \vee s</m> is false, then both <m>r</m> and <m>s</m> must be false. Thus <m>p</m> is true, <m>q</m> is true, <m>r</m> is false, and <m>s</m> is false.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </exercise>

