    <exercise workspace="0.25in">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Define the following propositions

          <ul>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>j</m>: Sally got the job.
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                <m>l</m>: Sally was late for her interview.
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                <m>r</m>: Sally updated her resume.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ul>

          Find logical expressions best expressing each pair of sentences below, then prove or disprove that the two expressions are logically equivalent.
        </p>

        <p>
          <ol marker="(a)">
            <li>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    If Sally did not get the job, then she was late for her interview or did not update her resume.
                  </p>
                </li>

                <li>
                  <p>
                    If Sally updated her resume and did not get the job, then she was late for her interview.
                  </p>
                </li>
              </ul>
            </li>
            <li>
             <ul>
              <li>
                <p>
                  If Sally did not get the job, then she was late for her interview or did not update her resume.
                </p>
              </li>

              <li>
                <p>
                  If Sally updated her resume and did not get the job, then she was late for her interview.
                </p>
              </li>
            </ul>
          </li>
          <li>

            <ul>
              <li>
                <p>
                  If Sally did not get the job, then she was late for her interview or did not update her resume.
                </p>
              </li>

              <li>
                <p>
                  If Sally updated her resume and was not late for her interview, then she got the job.
                </p>
              </li>
            </ul>
          </li>
          <li>
            <ul>
              <li>
                <p>
                  If Sally updated her resume or she was not late for her interview, then she got the job.
                </p>
              </li>

              <li>
                <p>
                  If Sally got the job, then she updated her resume and was not late for her interview.
                </p>
              </li>
            </ul>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </statement>

    <solution>
      <p>
        <ol marker="(a)">
          <li>
            <p>
              The first statement is best expressed as <m>\neg j \rightarrow l \vee \neg r</m>, and the second is best expressed as <m>r \wedge \neg j \rightarrow l</m>. To see the two statements are logically equivalent, we will show the two statements are both false in exactly one scenario: when <m>j</m> is false, <m>l</m> is false, and <m>r</m> is true.

              <ul>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    The statement <m>\neg j \rightarrow l \vee \neg r</m> is false when <m>\neg j</m> is true and <m>l \vee \neg r</m> is false. This only happens when <m>j</m> is false, <m>l</m> is false, and <m>r</m> is true.
                  </p>
                </li>

                <li>
                  <p>
                    The statement <m>r \wedge \neg j \rightarrow l</m> is false when <m>r \wedge \neg j</m> is true and <m>l</m> is false. This also only happens when <m>j</m> is false, <m>l</m> is false, and <m>r</m> is true.
                  </p>
                </li>
              </ul>

              Since <m>\neg j \rightarrow l \vee \neg r</m> and <m>r \wedge \neg j \rightarrow l</m> are both false in exactly the same circumstances, they are also both true in exactly the same circumstances, and thus truth functionally equivalent.
            </p>

            <p>
              Alternatively, one can show that the two statements are truth functionally equivalent by constructing a truth table, which shows the truth values of the two statements agree in all circumstances.
            </p>

