          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              The first statement is equivalent to <m>\neg j \rightarrow l \vee \neg r</m>, and the second is equivalent to <m>r \wedge \neg l \rightarrow j</m>. One way to see this is noting that the statements are contrapositives of one another, and any conditional statement is equivalent to it's contrapositive.
